Predictive Analytics Assign 1

Aim of Project

The Aim of the project was to try and create a simple Multi-Variate Regression model which could be used to predict a Worker’s Weekly Earnings.

To this end, the following model was created:

\[Weekly Earnings = 4.17 + (0.38 * Weekly Hrs Worked) + (1.07 * Education level) + (8.348 * Standard error)\]

Key Findings

  • Model performance was weak, likely due to weak data correlation

  • Weekly Wages are unsurprisingly dictated by both the Weekly Hours work and the Education Level of the employee.

  • Gender and Age also played a minor role, but were considered mostly insignificant.

Data Exploration

Firstly some simple variables were extracted

weeklyearnings <- csv$Weekly.Earnings
weeklyhrsworked <- csv$Weekly.Hours.Worked
age <- csv$Age
sleeping <- csv$Sleeping
socialising <-csv$Socializing...Relaxing
foodprep <- csv$Food...Drink.Prep
volunteering <- csv$Volunteering
employ <- csv$Employment.Status

Next Gender was converted to a binary variable ‘maleyes’ and Education.level was converted into a numeric variable

maleyes <- as.numeric(csv$Gender == "Male")

education <-  ifelse(csv$Education.Level == '9th Grade',1,
              ifelse(csv$Education.Level == '10th Grade',2,
              ifelse(csv$Education.Level == '11th Grade',3,
              ifelse(csv$Education.Level == '12th Grade',4,
              ifelse(csv$Education.Level == 'High School',5,
              ifelse(csv$Education.Level == 'Some College',6,
              ifelse(csv$Education.Level == 'Associate Degree',7,
              ifelse(csv$Education.Level == 'Bachelor',8,
              ifelse(csv$Education.Level == 'Master',9,
              ifelse(csv$Education.Level == 'Doctoral Degree',10,
              ifelse(csv$Education.Level == 'Doctoral Degree',11,0)))))))))))

A Preliminary Data frame was formed.

This data frame was then subset to remove all records which had 0 or less Hrs worked / Wages or unemployed workers

nozero <- subset(data,data[,2] >0)

nozero <- subset(nozero,nozero[,1] >0)

nozero <- subset(nozero,nozero[,3] == 'Employed')

Then a payrate column was created by dividing weekly wages by weekly hrs worked

nozero$payrate <- with(nozero, weeklyearnings / weeklyhrsworked)

Scatter plots 2

A correlation plot was created to see how the variables correlated together

As we can see in the plot, the data has pretty poor correlation between variables. Only weeklyhrsworked2 has over 0.5 which is still a weak correlation - we would likely expect weak performance from the predictive model as the data doesn’t correlate well.

A sample was then taken to split the data into 80% training, 20% test

indextrain <- sample.int(nrow(trans),round(nrow(trans) * 0.8))

trainingsample <- trans[indextrain,]
validationsample <- trans[-indextrain,]

Here we can see that the model has an Multiple R2 of ~0.33. This means the Model can only explain ~33% of the variance in the data. This is pretty poor performance; likely because the data input into the model is poor.

Predicting

Firstly Weekly Earnings were predicted on the training set

trainingsample$pred.weekearnings <- predict(fit4, newdata = subset(trainingsample, select = c(weeklyhrsworked2,education2)))

train.corr <- round(cor(trainingsample$pred.weekearnings, trainingsample$weeklyearnings2), 2) # 0.57 #
train.RMSE <- round(sqrt(mean((trainingsample$pred.weekearnings^2 - trainingsample$weeklyearnings2^2)^2))) # 543 #
train.MAE <- round(mean(abs(trainingsample$pred.weekearnings^2 - trainingsample$weeklyearnings2^2))) # 368 #
c("Correlation","RMSE","MAE")
## [1] "Correlation" "RMSE"        "MAE"
## [1]   0.3249 544.0000 366.0000
